{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brazil_ver03/data/sn83030214/00175039673/1910060201/0029.xml":{"full_text":"EASTERN ROADS ALSO\nHIT BY RATE ORDER\nSay Plans for Advances Are\nBlocked by the Western\ninjunction.\nIN DOUBT AS TO FUTURE\nOfficials Declare That Decreased\nShipmenis Are Likely to\nFollow Federal\nSuit.\nL0U0W rcoacial\nSuit.\nThe pians of the Eastern. railroads and\ntrunk lines for an early increase of freight\nrates have been knocked into a cocked hat\nby the granting of the injunction restrain\ning twenty-five Western roads from in\ncreasing their rates. The Eastern roads\nhave been holding conferences for some\ntime and have most of their new schedules\nready. Further conferences had been ar\nranged for the near future, and the entire\nnew schedule was to be ready for filing\nwith the Interstate Commerce Commission\nin time for the new rates to go into effect\nin the eariy fall.\nAn official of an Eastern road who has\nbeen busy on the work of preparing the\nnew schedules said yesterday that the con\nferences of the Eastern rcads had been\ncalled off. \u201cWe are all up in the air,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cWe can't tell what to do until this\n\u00abase has been settled. Our rate plans have\n8]1 gone to smash. If we can't get to\ngether and talk over rates, I don\u2019t know\nwhat we are going to do. It would be folly\nfor one road to try to increase rates by\nitself; that would he ruination to its busi\nness; but the roads can't pay the present\nwages and keep up the rate of dividends\nunless the freight rates are increased.\n\u201c1t should be taken into account that the\nincreased cost of lving hhs affected the\nrailroads as well as other lines of business,\nSupplies cost us more and we have to pay\nhigher wages. We have just come through\nsession with our emploves in which we\ngranted a general increase all along the\nline. Now, it looks as though we were to\nbe told that we can't raise our freight rates\n\u00a30 as to pay the higher wages.\n\u201cBut wait until\u201dthe railroads begin to lay\noff men and countermand orders for new\nequipment, and then the public will wake\nup to what this thing means. The country\nis mightily dependent on the railroads for\n{ts prosperity and it needs a good lesson.\nA protracted period of business depression\nwill teach the people to give the railroads\na chance.\u201d\nOpinion among railroad men had not had\ntime to crystallize yesterday and few of\nthem were ready to talk for publication.\nThey wanted time to get the text of the\ncourt order and more time to study the\nsituation. But the general feeling was one\nof anger and antagonism.\n\n\nView of J. B. Kerr.\nThe general feeling was thus pretty well\nexpressed. John B. Kerr, vice-president\nand general counsel of the New York, On\ntario Western, said:\n\n\u201cThere is no use speculating on business\nor what will happen te railroads under\npresent conditions. The one sure thing is\nthat anvihing unsettling to the railroads\nhurts business generally. A business man\nmust know his railroad rates, as well as\nthe price of bar iron. When the railroads\ncan\u2019t make a move without he government\ngoing after them there can't be anything\nstable about their affairs, and general busi\nress is going to be correspondingly un\nstable,\n\n\u201cThe Eastern roads may be affected by\nthis action in the West. It is likely to\nresult in decreased shipments and a falling\noff in the general business of the Eastern\nroads. There is no sign of a boom now,\nand such acrien will not help. Better times\nmay come in the fall, after Congress has\nadjourned and the people have had time to\nfind out where they are.\u201d\nW. H. Newman, former president of the\nNew York Central, sailed for Europe yes\nterday on the Adriatic. Before sailing he\ncaid of the injunction against the Western\nroads:\n\u201cI believe the sentiment of the country\ni= against the increase in rates. Tt may\npossibly mean great injury to business.\n\u00a3till, vou cannot tell what will happen in\nthe next forty-eight hours. I de not care fo\n#ay much about it. I am not now an ac\ntive railroad man, you know, but still I\nt2ke an active interest in what is going\non. Business conditions, as a rule, are\ngood. but this injunction may mean a eon-\nsiderable sethack.\u201d\nNewman Erb, chairman of the\n\nboard of the Ann Arbor Railroad, pointed\nout that the railroads were directed by one\nlaw to de a certain thing, while by another\nJaw they were forbidden to do the same\nthing.\n\u201cThe railroad companies do not wish to\ndo anvthing unlawful,\u201d he said, \u201cand are\nthemselves interested in knowing whether\niheir proceedings have been lawful. The\ninterstate commerce act requires them to\nunite in establishing through rates and\njoint tariffs for interstate business, and im\nposes severe penalties for violation of this\nprovision. The Sherman law prohibits\nYhem from uniting in agreements in re\nstraint of trade. Sc the railroaas are be\ninween two fires.\n\u201cThe question of whether the rates the\nrailroads now desire to establish are too\nhigh. or. rather, unreasonable, is not in-\nvolved in the present proceedings of the\ngovernment. The sole question is whether\nthe railroads have combined for the pur-\npose of establishing rates in restraint of\ntrade under the Sherman law. The Inter-\nstate (Commerce (Commission is the sole\u2019\ntribunal for the determination of the rea\nsonahleness or unreasonableness of rates.\n\"All other advances made by the rail\nroads remain undisturbed, and as railroads\nare left 10 advance thelr rates independently\nno serious injury to the railroad interests\nof the country is involved in the present\ngovernment proceedings. It is simply a\nquestion of obtaining a decision which ao\ndetermine whether the railroad companies\ncan unite in establishing joint tariffs under\ns\nThe pians of the Eastern. railroads and\ntrunk lines for an early increase of freight\nrates have been knocked into a cocked hat\nby the granting of the injunction restrain\ning twenty-five Western roads from in\ncreasing their rates. The Eastern roads\nhave been holding conferences for some\ntime and have most of their new schedules\nready. Further conferences had been ar\nranged for the near future, and the entire\nnew schedule was to be ready for filing\nwith the Interstate Commerce Commission\nin time for the new rates to go into effect\nin the early fall.\nAn official of an Eastern road who has\nbeen busy on the work of preparing the\nnew schedules said yesterday that the con\nferences of the Eastern rcads had been\ncalled off. \u201cWe are all up in the air,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cWe can't tell what to do until this\n\u00abase has been settled. Our rate plans have\n8]1 gone to smash. If we can't get to\ngether and talk over rates, I don\u2019t know\nwhat we are going to do. It would be folly\nfor one road to try to increase rates by\nitself; that would he ruination to its busi\nness: but the roads can't pay the present\nwages and keep up the rate of dividends\nunless the freight rates are increased.\n\u201c1t should be taken into account that the\nincreased cost of Mving his affected the\nrailroads as well as other lines of business.\nSupplies cost us more and we have to pay\nhigher wages. We have just come through\nsession with our emploves in which we\ngranted a general increase all along the\nline. Now, it looks as though we were to\nbe told that we can't raise our freight rates\n\u00a30 as to pay the higher wages.\n\u201cBut wait until\u201dthe railroads begin to lay\noff men and countermand orders for new\nequipment, and then the public will wake\nup to what this thing means. The country\nis mightily dependent on the railroads for\n{ts prosperity and it needs a good lesson.\nA protracted period of business depression\nwill teach the people to give the railroads\na chance.\u201d\nOpinion among railroad men had not had\ntime to crystallize yesterday and few of\nthem were ready to talk for publication.\nThey wanted time to get the text of the\ncourt order and more time to study the\nsituation. But the general feeling was one\nView of J. B. Kerr.\nNeed a Cook?\nYou will find a good one by\nreading the \u201cWant Ads.\u201d\n\u201cQuality\u201d help is character\nistic of the \u201cquality want\ncolumns.\nTHE TRIBUNE,\na\n154 Nassau St\n1364 Broadway.\nUptowr,\nthe Sherman law which they are required\nJ\nto do under the interstate commerce act.\u201d\nGeneral Thomas H. Hubbard, who is a\ndirector in the Chicago Alton, the To\nledo, St. Louis Western and the Wa\nbash, and a close associate of Edwin Haw\nley and R. FF. Yoakum, said:\n\u201cIt would have been better\u2014decidedly\nbetter\u2014if the administration had not taken\nsides in the matter of increased freight\nrates. This matter should have been left\nto the determination of the Interstaie om\nmerce (Commission on application of ship\n\npers. That is all 1 care to say on the sub\nject, although I may add that there is no\ndoubt railroad rates throughout the coun\ntry are Jlow\u2014entirely too ilow-\u2014in many\ncases.\u201d\n\nMany railroad men took the view\nthat shippers generally did not object to\nan increase in freight rates, thougn it is\nunderstood that the .government\u2019's action\nwas taken at the request of the Western\nshippers\u2019 associations. The view of rail\nroad men here was supported by John C.\nEames, vice-president of the H. B. Claflin\n\u2018Company, one of the largest vhippers of\ndrygoods in this country. Mr. Eames sain:\n\u201cThere is no reason why shippers should\noffer any great objection to the railroads\nincreasing their freight rates as long as no\ndiscrimination is practised. Both passen\nger and freight rates are lower in this\ncountry than in Europe, and the advance\nwhich was contemplated was not an ex\norbitant one. As long as the increase is\nan equitable one, there is no cause for the\npresent violent agitation, which is likely to\ngive a setback to general business.\u201d\nA pessimistic outlook for general busi\nness was taken also by Theodore Voorhees,\nvice-president of the Reading, who was a\npassenger with W. H. Newman on the\nAdriatic. Mr. Voorhees is going abroad to\nattend the International Railway Congress\nat Berne. He said:\n\u201cAll this action by the government\nagainst the railway industry is bound to\n\nhave a disastrous effect. This injunction\nproceeding had not been expected. \"Rail\nroad men have hoped that the government\nwould give them a better deal than appears\nto have been obtained. The carrying of\nfreight 1s, of course, a work which has a\nvery direct bearing on every industry, and\nany action hindering the proper carrying on\nof such work should he given very careful\nconsideration. Alreadv there is a general\ndepression throughout the country as a re\nsult of the overdose of legislative action\nagainst railway enterprises.\u201d\nChicago dispatches quoted President Fel\nton of the Great Western, who said:\n\u201cI'm consulting our attorneys regarding\nthe rate injunction, and presume other\nroads are doing the same. The railroads\nare not working together. We are all in\nthe dark untii we know more about the\nsituation. Certainly we didn't anticipate\nthis development. All I know this far is\nwhat newspapers say, and until I receive\nfull official information I cannot discuss\nthe matter or reach any conclusion regar\u00e9\ning either the rate injunction or the Mis\nsouri River rata decision.\u201d\n\n\n\n\n\u201cYou just wait until I get hold of Wicker\nsham, and I'll teli him a few things,\u201d was\nthe farewell of Henry Phipps, as he sailed\non the Adriatic.\n\nMR. WICKERSHAM EXPLAINS\nRailroad Suit Handled Secretly\u2014\nAll Increases Not Prevented.\nWashington, June 1.\u2014-Attorney General\nWickersham talked somewhat freely to\nday regarding the steps which led up to\nthe administration move against the rail\nroads. The first intimation he had of the\nconditions alleged, he said. was in a dis\npatch which came from somewhere in the\nFn last Thursday, but this, being wholly\na by details,, did not impress\n\n\n\n\n\nhim very seriously.\nFriday more dispatches came, and Rep\nresentative Hubbard, of Towa, gave him a\ncomprehensive statement of the situation.\nThis convinced him, Mr. Wickersham said,\nthat action ought to be taken. He at ence\ngot together, with the assistance of the In\nterstate Commerce Commission, all data\navailable and spent the following two days\nin the preparation of the bill in equity.\nThe Interstate Commerce Commission fur\nnished affidavits that the tariffs ecom\nplained of had been filed with that body,\nwhat thev showed, and that an agent had\nbeen employed at Washington to file them.\nSunday night Mr. Grosvenor was sent to\nSt. TL,ouis with the bill in equity and the\naffidavits in his possession.\ni\n\nProceedings against the railroads were\nbrought in the 8th Judicial Cirenit, Mr.\nWickersham said, because the anti-trust\nlaw had received fits fullest interprefation\nin that circuit, a notable case being that\nof the government against the Standard Oil\nCompany.\n\nThrough the secrecy with which the case\nwas handled the government circumvented\nthe railroads and obtained the restraining\norder without the roads having any chance\nto be heard in oposition to the application.\nHad they been permitted to appear in op\nposition, the result probably would have\nbeen more or less delayed, and meantime\nthe increased rates would have gone into\neffect. It was on this account that, al\nthough Mr. Wickersham had determined\non a course to pursue, he purposely re\nfrained from making known his intentions\nto the Omaha committee which appeared\nbefore him on Memorial Day.\n\n\ni\ni\n\n\nThe rates which were prevented from\n\nbecoming effective at midnight last night\ned the temporary injunction granted con\nstitute only a part of the advances made\n\u2018by the Western Trunk Line Association.\nThe injunction applies only to Tariff A 115,\n\u2018mentioned in the bill filed before the Cir\ncuit Court by representatives of the De\npartment of Justice. The tariffs filed prac\ntically simultaneously with the Interstate\nCommerce Commission by the Western\nTrunk Line Association, making advances\nin the rates on commodities between Chi\ncago and Milwaukee and between Chicago\nand St. Paul and between St. Paul and\nEastern destinations on wool are in effect\nto-day.\nWhile these tariffs are not so important\nas those making general advances on com\n modities between Missouri and Mississippi\nRiver points, they, nevertheless, are of con\nsiderable concern to shippers in Western\nTrunk Line territory to Atlantic seaboard\npoints. The increase in the rate on wool\nfrom St. Paul points to New York and\nBoston particularly is of immense interest\nto consigners, as it means a flat advance of\n10 cents a hundred pounds. This increase\napplies to all Western wool passing\u2019\n\u2018through Minneapolis or St. Paul to Atlantic\ntidewater destinations.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nIt is not explained why the injunction\nsought by the Department of Justice was\nnot made applicable to gil the advances re\ncently made by the Western Trunk Line\nAssociation.\n\nSt. Louis, June 1l.\u2014Frederick N. Judson,\nspecial counsel for the gevernment in the\ninjunction case against the Western rall\nroads, said to-night that if anything had\nbeen, omitted in the petition filed yesterday\nhe did not know of it. The petition was\nnrenared in Wachineoton\n\nSt. Louis, June l.\u2014Frederick N. Judson,\nspecial counsel for the gevernment in the\ninjunction case against the Western rall\nroads, sald to-night that if anything had\nbeen, omitted in the petition filed yesterday\nhe did not know of it. The petition was\nnrepared in Washington.\nSANTA FE RAISES WAGES.\nTopeka, Kan, June 1 \u2014Announcement\nwas made to-day that all the employes of\nthe Atchison, Topeka Santa Fe railway\nreceiving less than $80 a month have been\ngranted an increase of 16 per cent in\nwages. The raise went into effect to-day.\nBIG JUMP FOR PATROL MAN.\nFor the first time in the history of the\nPolice Department 5 patrolman was raised\nyesterday to a place in the depar'ment\nwhich is equivalent in pay to that of police\ncaptzin. William Allen, who has been on\nthe force for twenty-one vears, was made\nsuperintendent of telegraph, to have charge\nof the police telephone and telegraph svs\ntem in Brooklyn, following a Civil Service\nexamination. Iis salary will be $2,750 a\nyear. As patrciman his salary was $1,300,\ni\n\nSt. Louis, June 1.\u2014Within the next two\ndays attorneys for the twenty-five Western\nrailroads temporarily restrained vesterday\nfrom advancing freight rates by Judge\nDavid P. Dyer, of the United States Dis\ntrict Court, will meet in St. T.ouis to plan\nan answer to the government's suit. It\nwas announced to-night by an attorney for\none of the roads that Attorney General\nWickersham\u2019s petition for a permanent in\njunction would be bitterly contested.\n\nThe principal ground on which the suit\nwill be fought is the contention that there\nis an agreement among the railroads to\nadvance freight rates, in violation of the\nSherman law,\nIf any agreement at all is admitted the\nrailroad companies will contend that it i8\nlegal in every respect and thar it is neces\n\u2018sary, because of present industrial econdi\n\u2018tions, to protect the interests of the gen\neral public.\n~The fact that the railroads are members\nof the Western Trunk Line Committee, a\nrailroad officer said, did not indicate that\nthey were in an agreement, because the\nschedule of rates promulgated by the com\nmittee was not binding on tne different\nmembers without their express consent.\nIt is sald at the various railroad head\nquarters that the enjoined rates might have\nbeen collected at distant points to-day, be\ncause rscinding orders had not had time to\nreach them.\nRailroad officers, so far as they could,\nobeved the court's order even before ser\nvice was made. They were greatly sur\nprised at the secrecy with which the gov\nernment\u2019s petition was filed yesterday, and\nwere not prepared for action.\nOfficers sald that most of the railroads\nhad anticipated the increased revenue\nwhich the new rates would bring, and had\nplanned extensive improvements, which\nprobably will be held up pending litigation.\nOne broker in railroad supplies sald he had\nalready received several cancellations on\norders from the railroad companies affected\nby the injunction.\nThe restraining order was placed in the\nhands of a T'nited States marshal to-night\nfor service to-morrow on three of the com\npanies having general offices in St. Louis.\nCopies of the order were sent to Chicago,\nKansas City, St. Paul and Parsons, Kan,\nwhere the twenty-two other railroads have\ntheir general offices.\n\nFollowing the filing to-day of a request\nto expedite the hearing of the case, it was\nannounced that Judges Adams, Vande\nventer, Hook and Sanborn, of the United\nStates Circuit Court, may take it up before\nthe vacation season. In that event the\nhearing would take place ih St. Paul,\nwhere the judges are now sitting.\nThe temporary restraining order was cer\ntified to the T'nited States Circuit Court\nhere this morning. Under orders from At\ntorney General Wickersham an expediting\ncertificate, providing for a speedy deter\nmination of the issues, was filed. A copy\nof the expediting order was mailed to\nJudges Hook, Sanborn, Vandeventer and\nAdams.\n\nT'nder tha expedition certificate in\njun-~tion suit will have precedence over all\nother cases docketed in the court. Twice\nin the history of the T'nited States\nhave such certificates been\nde\n\nthe\nonly\nCircuit Court\nfiled here. In the Standard Oil case,\ncided in favor of the government by the\nCirenit Court of Appeals, composed of the\n\nsame jndges who will hear the railroad in\n\njunction suit, and in the suit to dissolve\nthe Terminal Railroad Association of St.\nLouis, expediting certificates were resorted\nto for obtaining a hearing. The\nrailroads can file a motion to dissolve the\nrestraining order at any time. If they do\nnot do this tkev can file their answer on\nthe first Monday in July in the equity side\nof the Circuit Court.\n\nSneecy\nDECRIES FIGHT ON RATES\nMove to Escape Tariff \u201c\u2018Blun\nders.\u201d Savs M. C. A. Speaker.\nDECRIES FIGHT ON RATES\nIn an address before the Finance Forum\nof the West Side Young Men's Christian\nAssociation last night William C. Cornwell,\nof J. S. Bache (o., said the action of\nthe President and the Attorney General in\nseeking tou enjoin the Western railroads\nfrom increasing rates was an attempt to\ndraw attention from the administration's\ntariff blunders.\n\nHe condemned the Sherman anti-trust\nlaw and declared that what was needed\nwas a business men's party, which, car\nried on upon sane and sound business prin\nciples, would hold the balance of power\nagainst politicians bent only on building\nup their own selfish interests and blindly\nsweeping the country toward destruction.\n\n\n\n\u201c1f attacks on railroad and industrial\ninterests continue,\u201d he sald, \u201cwe must be\nprepared for a renewed setback in busi\nness. The crops may bring us partially\nout of this, but with the Sherman ,law\nhanging over us, the deadly hostility of the\nadministration against business progress\nmaintained and currency inflation looming\nlarge ahead of us, 1910 will be our last year\nof reasonable prosperity for a long time to\ncome.\u201d\n\nMr. Cornwell said that if the government\nwere a business institution, controlled by\nbusiness common sense, its efforts long ago\nwould have been applied to devising a\nmethod of relief by amendment of the Sher\nman anti-trust law. He said President\nTaft announced soon after his election that\nit was his purpose to bring this about, but\nhe had changed his mind, being actuated\nprobably by the necessity of converting thas\nbitter enmity of the voting consumer into\nfriendship by action apparently in his in\nrest\n\nRailroads and Shippers Want It in\nMissouri Rate Cases.\n\n\nWashington, June 1.\u2014With the probabil\nity of two more members being on the\nbench next Octoher, the railroads hetween\nthe Mississippi and Missouri rivers and\nshippers in the central! freight territory\nare said to he preparing to ask for a re\nhearing\u2019 of the Missouri River rate cases,\ndecided yesterday by the Supreme Court\nof the United States in favor of the In\nterstate Commerce Commission. The de\ncision was supported by only four mem\nbers of the court, and {if a rehearing could\nbe had that number would not be suffi\ncient to overrule the district court, which\nheld the rates invalid.\n\n\nThe order of the court putting the re\nduced rates into effect will be held thirty\ndays to allow the roads to file an applica\ntion for a rehearing. If this is done, the\napplication cannot be passed on until next\nOctober. By that time Governor Hughes\nof New York will have taken his place on\nthe bench and Justice Moody may have re\nsumed work. In these two members the\nroads see some hope of a rehearingz.\n\nJ. A. Harzfeld, a lawyer and former\nnewspaper man. who has just been appoint\ned by the Mavor of Kansas ity as the\nchairman of the Public Service Commission\nof that efty, is in New York studying the\nworking of the Public Kepvice Commission.\nKansas City formeriy had a board of seven\ncorarnissioners, but this proved unsatis\nfactory, and now the number BAS De\u00e9en re\nCuced to three.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nRAILROADS PLAN FIGHT\nDeny That They Have Viclated\nAnti-Trust Law.\nSTOPPING IMPROVEMENTS\nThough Taken by Surprise,\nRoads Obey Order\u2014Suit To\nBe Expedited.\nMAY ASK A REHEARING\n\nSTUDYING NEW YORK P. C.\nRAILROAD STOCKS HARD HIT\nSevere Break on N. Y. Exchange\nFollowing Federal Injunction.\nDuring the greater part ol yesterday Ss\ncession the stock market was in a state\nof demoralization more serious than had\nbeen experienced for several months, with\nthe railroad issues the chief sufferers. The\nbreak which followed the overnight news\nthat the government had secured a tem\nporary order restraining the proposed ad\nvance of freight rates by twenty-five roads\nof the Middle West. was a continuation of\nthe decline of Tuesday, resulting from the\nannouncement of the intention of the ad\nministration to take legal sieps against\nthe plan of the roads, but was much more\nsevere.\n\nDeclines of 3 to 4 points were suffered by\nmany railway stocks, an extreme loss of\n714 peints being recorded for St. Paul; and\na number of issues, among them Union Pa\ncific, Southern Pacific, Atchison, Great\nNorthern and Northern Pacific, touched\nnew low levels for the year. Total sales\nwere 1,202,990 shares, or nearly double the\ntransactions of Tuesday.\n\nShort selling of the railroad list was\nconducted on a heavy scale during the\nearly trading, and there was also apparent\nextensive liquidation, that in St. Paul being\nsaid to be partly for account of interests\nwhich had acquired large amounts of the\nstock in connection with recently closed\nnegotiations for placing $50,000,000 debentures\nin France, On the way down many in\nsufficiently margined commission house ac\ncounts were closed out, their aggregate be\ning large enough to figure as a factor in the\ndecline.\nLondon was a purchaser on balance to\nthe amount of 30,000 or $0,002 shares, princi\nrally of Steel common, and this buying\nwas durinz the morning hours almost the\nonly steadying influence, the only other\nbuying demand being represented in the\ncovering of shorts in various stocks. Steel\ncommon, in which the sales were nearly\n300,000 shares, was the only important issue\nin which support was evident during the\nday. It opened at 795, and reached its low\nof 7815 a little before noon.\nIn the late trading good buying orders\nwere put in by banking interests, and this\nmovement, supplemented by covering of\nshort contracts, caused a substantial rally,\nfinal prices of active issues being from 1\nto 3 points above the lowest, although\nshowing net losses for the day of from 1\nto 2 points. Two notable exceptions were\nSt. Paul, which closed 61; points lower than\non Tuesday, and Steel common, in which\nthe net decline was only 13 point,\n\nThe severity of tha decline induced by the\ngovernment's move against the Western\nrailways may be judged from the following\ntable:\nHigh. Low. Maximum\nStock. Tuesday. Wednesday. decline.\nUnion Pacific ..........188% 175 8\nSouthern Pacific .......128 1183 T%\nSt. Paul... ..crecans--309 129% 2%\nReading. .....--cescavss 162% 153 Gog\nAitchison .......caseenus 106 7 10235 87g\nNorthern Pacific eens 131 125 [3\nGreat Northern ........13473 130 47s\nMissouri Pacific 71% 8512 3\nMo... Kan Texas..... 41%; 383% 2%,\nChic. Northwestern. .152 14712 4%\nNew York Central ....1197 114%; Hig\nPennsylvania 1347 1203, 5's\nTU. 8 Steel common. 827% Rig EEA\nAmalgamated Copper... T0% 6H 3%g 47%\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAmer, 8S. RBR........, 70's 4 O's\n\u2018MUST PRODUCE LADY COOK\nTennessee Claflin\u2019s Sister Makes\nCharges Against Her Friends.\nDeclaring that Lady Cook, pioneer in the\nsuffrage movement, and formerly Miss\nTennessee CC. Claflin, was being deprived\nof ber liberty by John Floyd Hume and\nhis wife, Mrs. Mabel Hume, at their home,\nNo. 10 West 61st street, Miss Mary Sparr,\na sister of Lady Cook, obtained a writ of\nhabeas corpus from Justice McCall yester\nday, directing that the Humes produce\nLady Cook in court forthwith.\n\ni\nMrs. Sparr says in her petition that her\nsister, who has had an exciting and spec\ntacular career, is an old woman and feeble.\nShe states on information and belief that\nMr. and Mrs. Hume intended to separate\nLady Cook from her family and friends\nand that they intended to obtain possession\nof the old woman's large estate. Mrs.\nSparr alleges that Lady Cook, not realizing\nthe consequence: of her acts and not being\nof sufficiently strong mind to withstand\nthe ipfluence and power of Mr. and Mrs.\nHum\u00ae, had already given them money and\ndocuments of which she does not know the\ncontents. Mrs. Sparr also alleges in her\npetition that the persons to whom the writ\nwas directed intended to spirit Lady Cook\nout of the jurisdiction of the court.\n\n\n\nJolim Floyd Hume, who is a copy reader\non a local newspaper, said last night that\nMillard F. Sparr, the petitioner's son, who\nis IL.ady Cook's business manager, had\npointed out to his mother that she was in\nerror, and that Mrs. Sparr had consented\nto withdraw her action when it comes up\nin the Supreme Court to-day. Hume said\nthat papers to that effect had been signed.\nHume added that Mrs. Sparr and Lady\nCook have not been on good terms and that\nLady Cook has refused to sec her sister,\nHe ridiculed the charges made by Mrs.\nSparr.\n\n\n\nJt was also explained that Lady Cook\nhad made her home with the Hume family\nwhen in New York for several years. Mrs.\nHume has accompanied her on several trips\nto Europe. Lady Cook's estate is said to\nbe entailed under \u2018the laws of England, so\nonly these persons entitled to inherit it can\nreceive any part of it.\n\n\nREVISED BOOK OF PSALMS\nAdopted by Presbyterians After Bitter\nOpposition.\nPhiladelphia, June 1.\u2014A revised book of\nPsalms was adopted at to-day\u2019s session of\nthe General Assembly of the United Pres\nbyterian Church, after a spirited discus\nsion.\n\nThe Rev. W. A. Campbell, of Mercer,\nPenn., led the opposition to the revised\nbook. He said he had expected the re\nvision committee to give the Church the\nbest version of the Psalms the world has\never seen in point of faithfulness and lit\nerary merit, but, he added, \u2018\u2018they have\ngiven us the worst version that has ever\nbeen seen.\n**The book shows,\u201d he said, \u201cthat it con\ntains imitations that our fathers condemned\nfor nearly two hundred years as human\nbyvmns, and it also contains free render\nings that are nothing but human hymns.\u201d\n\n\ni\n\u201cThe question,\u201d said tht Rev. Mr. Camp\nbell, \u2018is, shall we reject these new psalms\nand live as a psalm-singing church, or\nshall we adopt them and become a hvmn\nsinging church, and thus see one of the\nnoblest psaim-singing churches pass out of\nexistence.\u201d\nIn conclusion, he said that if the new\nversion was adopted no good reason could\nbe given for remaining separate from the\nPreshvterian Chureh.\nTOWER GIVES ALIMONY BOND\nWealthy Manufacturer Denies That He\nWill Remove to California Ranch.\nAlbert FE. Tower, the wealthy iron and\nsteel manufacturer, of Poughkeepsie, was\nordered yesterday to filc a bond of $200,000\nas security that he would continue to pay\nhis wife, Mary Bogardus Tower, of White\n\nPlaine, the sum of $1 monthly alimony,\nas directed by Supreme Court Justice Keogh\nabout a year ago. The wife, who then se\ncured a separation from him, made appli\ncation recently to have him file a bond to\nsecure the alimony payments, on the ground\nthat he was about to remove to Pasadena,\nCal.,, where she said he had purchased an\nimmense ranch.\n\n\n\nIn his defence Tower sald he never had\nany intention of giving up his residence\nhere, but had bought the ranch ou} West\nto live thera anly temporarily\nADVANCE ON COAL POSTPONED.\nWashington, June 1 Rates on coal from\nIilinois and Indiana mines to Chicago and\nto points basing on Chicago, which were\nto be effective to-day, have been postponed\nungil July I5, The change proposed was a\nflat advance of 10 cents a ten.\nJ. HILL NOT WORRIED\nJ. HILL NOT WORRIED\n14 THURSDAY, New 0 ork Tribmue. JUNE 2. 1910.\nHints That Railroads May Fight\nFreight Injunction.\nEARNINGS ARE INCREASED\nNo Sales of Securities Abroad\u2014\nCrop Equipment Ready and\nCars in Plenty.\nHints That Railroads May Fight\nFreight Injunction.\nEARNINGS ARE INCREASED\nNo Sales of Securities Abroad\u2014\nCrop Equipment Ready and\nCars in Plenty.\n\u201cThis country has survived many stupid\nthings, and I think it will survive this pro\nceeding,\u201d said James J. Hill, chairman of\nthe board of directors of the Great North\nern Railway, wien asked yesterday for his\nopinion regarding the injunction secured\nby the government restraining twenty-five\nWestern railroads from putting in effect\n{rcreases in their freight schedules.\nFurther than tnis Mr. Hill refused to\ncomment on the subject, except to say that\nit reminded him of a case \u2018n which a man\nsought to get possession of a farm to which\nhe had no legal claim. The jury, Mr. Hill\nsaid, nevertheless brought in a verdict in\nfavor of the plaintiff, which the judge\npromptly set aside, remarking that it would\ntake thirteen men in any court over which\nhe presided to steal a man's farm away\nfrom him.\n\u201cYou cee,\u201d went on Mr. Hill, \u201cthere was\na higher authority than the jury that de\ntermined that case, and in this injunction\nproceeding there is also a higher author\nity.\u201d\nWhat the \u201chigher authority\u2019 was in the\npresent instance Mr. Hill did not say, but\nit is supposed that he meant the United\nStates Supreme Court, which would indi\ncate that the railroads mean to carry the\ncase to the court of last resort if neces\nsary.\nMr. Hill returned here only vesterday\nfrom the Northwest, where he had been for\nseveral weeks. While away he made an\nextensive trip over the Northern Pacific\nand Great Northern roads in company with\na numter of bankers and railroad men, in\ncluding George F. Baker, chairman of the\nboard of directors of the First National\nBank, and Charles Steele, of J. P. Mor\ngan Co.\n\n\nSpeaking of this trip Mr. Hill said that\nhe had found the condition of the roads\nentirely satisfactory, that crops in their\nterritory were excellent and promised an\nabundant harvest, and that business in\ngeneral in the Northwest showed steady\nimprovement. An indication of how busi\nness had improved, he said, was the fact\nthat the earnings of the Great Northern\nand Northern Pacific showed an increase\nof about 39,000,000 this vear over the same\nperiod a year ago. He added that he did\nnot believe the government suit would\nhave any effect on business in jhe North\nwest, as people out there were too busy\nto pay much attention to such things.\n\n\n\n\nAsked as to the truth of reports that\nthe Great Northern and Northern Pacific\nwere going to follow the recent example\nof the St. Paul and the \u201cBig Four\u201d in\nselling securities abroad, Mr. Hill said\nthat they were not contemplating any\nthing of the kind. \u201cThese rumors of pros\npective financing are put out here,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cfor some purpose or other, but there\nis no foundation for them so far as I\nam aware.\u201d\nSpeaking of the ability of the railroads\nto handle the bumper erops, of which\nthere was every promise this fall, Mr.\nHill predicted that there would be no dif-\nculty in that direction so far as his lines\nwere concerned. \u201cWith our equipment,\u201d\nhe added, \u201cwe could transport all the,\ngrain grown in our territory to the sea-\nhoard in four trips.\u201d\n\nIf there was any delay, he said, in hand-\ning the crops on the part of the railroads,\nt would not be caused by lack of cars,\nhut through lack of adequate terminal!\nFacilities.\n\n\nWOULD PAY FOR NEW ROUTE\nEast Flatbush Property Owners Join in\nPetition for Rapid Transit.\nEast Flatbush wants a rapid transit line,\npart subway and more elevated, and offers\nto pay for the new route. A petition bear\ning 1,002 signatures of proprietors was pre\nsented yesterday to the Public Service\nCommission by G. J. Luhn, chairman of\nthe committee on railroads and trans\nportation of the East Flatbush Taxpayers\u2019\nAssociation, asking the commission to lay\nout a three mile and a half route from\nEastern Parkway, down Utica avenue to\nFlatbush avenue, and out Flatbush avenue\nto Jamaica Bay.\n\n\nOnly the portion near Eastern Parkway\nwould be subway, and the conformation of\nthe ground is such that no steep grade\nwould be caused by the change from sub\n\n\nway to elevated construction.\ni\nThis is the third petition for the building\nof a rapid transit route by assessment.\nThe idea is to join Jamaica Bay with Union\nSquare, Manhattan, by way of the pro\nposed Eastern Parkway subway.\nf\n\n\n\nCROWD AT SEA BREEZE OPENING.\n\nThe New York Association for Improving\nthe Condition of the Poor opened its home\nat Sea Breeze, West Coney Island, yester\nday. In the first party there were 163\nmothers and children. Frederick D. Greene,\nof the association, said that thirty thou\nsand guests will be housed at the home\nduring the season.\ni\n\nMARINE INTELLIGENCE.\nMINIATURE ALMANAC.\n\n\u201cHh 3\nAFL ALANA A LENE ARASTR EN ANA an\nSunrise, 4:32; sunset, 7:24; moon rises, 1:41;\nmoon's age, 24.\n\n\nA\nSandy HOOK ......cccvinismmennncsnn\nCcvernor's Isiand\ni 1\n\nssssne Trane\n\noe.\nHell Gate 3. .cicidinay cRTeat ant 4\nWIRE! ESS REPORTS\nThe Lusitania, reported as S77 miles east of\nSandy Hook at noon yesterday, is expected to\ndock Friday forenoon.\n\n\nLa Savoie, reported as 1.128 miles east of\nSandy Hook at 2 p m yesterday, is expected to\ndock late Friday evening or Saturday forenoon.\n\n\nH\nor\n\u2018The President Grant, reported as 193 miles\neast of Sandy Hook at 8 a m yesterday, is ex\npected to dock this ferenoon.\nThe Teutonic, reported as 313 miles east of\nSandy Hook at T a m yesterday, is expected to\ndock this forenoon.\niy\nINCOMING STEAMERS.\nRv. 43 St Fy\nSa 1\n\nVessel. From. Line.\n\n\nSANOOMN. von ..Cristobal, May 25.....Panama\n*l.usitania. .Liverpool, May 28. Cunard\n*Teutonic....... Southampton, May 25. Rg Star\n\nPresident Grant... Southampton, May 3 ah Am\nriedrich der G. ..Palermo, May 21....N G Lloyd\nFioride. Havre, May J1. ..French\nRe d'Italfa....... A008, May A eg Italian\nAntiiies.......... New O